<nowiki>*</nowiki> The sounds in parentheses ''f, r, l'' occur only in loanwords from English.<ref>Rhodes, Richard, 1985, pp. xlv, xlvii, liii</ref>

The [[plosive]], [[Fricative consonant|fricative]], and [[Affricate consonant|affricate]] consonants are divided into two sets, referred to as [[fortis and lenis]]. Fortis (or "strong") consonants are typically distinguished from lenis (or "weak") consonants by features such as greater duration or [[Gemination|length]], are [[Voice (phonetics)|voiceless]] where lenis consonants are typically [[Voice (phonetics)|voiced]], and may be [[Aspiration (phonetics)|aspirated]].<ref>Nichols, John and Earl Nyholm, 1995, p. xxxvi</ref><ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 48<U+2013>49</ref> In Ottawa, each fortis consonant is matched to a corresponding lenis consonant with the same [[place of articulation]] and [[manner of articulation]]. Ottawa fortis consonants are voiceless and phonetically long,<ref name="Rhodes, Richard, 1985">Rhodes, Richard, 1985, pp. xlix<U+2013>l, l<U+2013>li, xlvii,</ref> and  are aspirated in most positions: {{IPA|[p<U+02D0><U+02B0>]}}, {{IPA|[t<U+02D0><U+02B0>]}}, {{IPA|[k<U+02D0><U+02B0>]}}, {{IPA|[t<U+0283><U+02D0><U+02B0>]}}. When following another consonant they are unaspirated or weakly articulated.<ref>Rhodes, Richard, 1985, p. xlvii</ref> The lenis consonants are typically voiced between vowels and word-initially before a vowel, but are [[Voice (phonetics)|devoiced]] in word-final position. The lenis consonants are subject to other [[Ottawa phonology#Secondary consonant clusters|phonological processes]] when adjacent to fortis consonants.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 74<U+2013>81</ref>

[[Labialisation|Labialized]] stop consonants {{IPA|[<U+0261><U+02B7>]}} and {{IPA|[k<U+02B7>]}}, consisting of a consonant with noticeable lip [[Roundedness|rounding]], occur in the speech of some speakers. Labialization is not normally indicated in writing, but a subscript dot is utilized in a widely used dictionary of Ottawa and Eastern Ojibwe to mark labialization: ''{{unicode|<U+0261><U+0323>taaji}}'' "he is afraid" and ''{{unicode|aa<U+1E33>zi}}'' "he is sick".<ref>Rhodes, Richard, 1985, pp. xvlvi, xlvii</ref>

===Vowels===
Ottawa has seven oral [[vowel]]s, four [[Vowel length|long]] and three [[Vowel length|short]]. There are four long nasal vowels whose status as either phonemes or [[allophone]]s (predictable variants) is unclear.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 34<U+2013>41</ref> The long vowels {{IPA|/i<U+02D0>, o<U+02D0>, a<U+02D0>/}} are paired with the short vowels {{IPA|/i, o, a/}},<ref name="Rhodes, Richard, 1985, pp. xxxix<U+2013>xliii"/> and are written with double symbols ''ii, oo, aa'' that correspond to the single symbols used for the short vowels ''i, o, a''. The long vowel {{IPA|/e<U+02D0>/}} does not have a corresponding short vowel, and is written with a single ''e''.<ref>Rhodes, Richard, 1985, p. xlii</ref> The phonological distinction between long and short vowels plays a significant role in Ottawa phonology, as only short vowels can be [[Ottawa phonology#Metrical feet and syllable weight|metrically weak]] and undergo [[Ottawa phonology#Vowel syncope|syncope]]. Long vowels are always [[Ottawa phonology#Metrical feet and syllable weight|metrically strong]] and never undergo deletion.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, p. 54</ref>

The table below gives the orthographic symbol and the primary phonetic values for each vowel.<ref>Rhodes, Richard, 1985, pp. xxxix-xlii</ref>

