| align="center"| aa {{IPA|[<U+0251><U+02D0>]}}
|-
|
|
| align="center"| a {{IPA|[<U+0259>]}}~{{IPA|[<U+0251>]}}
|}

The long nasal vowels are ''iinh'' ({{IPA|[<U+0129><U+02D0>]}}), ''enh'' ({{IPA|[<U+1EBD><U+02D0>]}}), ''aanh'' ({{IPA|[<U+00E3><U+02D0>]}}), and ''oonh'' ({{IPA|[<U+00F5><U+02D0>]}}). They most commonly occur in the final syllable of nouns with [[diminutive]] suffixes or words with a diminutive connotation,<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 185<U+2013>188</ref> as well as in the suffix ''(y)aanh'' ([-{{IPA|(j)<U+00E3><U+02D0>]}}) 'first person (Conjunct) Animate Intransitive'.<ref name="Valentine, J. Randolph 2001, p. 19">Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, p. 19</ref> Orthographically the long vowel is followed by word-final ''nh'' to indicate that the vowel is nasal; while ''n'' is a common indicator of nasality in many languages such as French, the use of ''h'' is an orthographic convention and does not correspond to an independent sound.<ref name="Valentine_NASAL_40">Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, p. 40</ref> One analysis treats the long nasal vowels as [[Phoneme|phonemic]],<ref>Bloomfield, Leonard, 1958, p. 7</ref> while another treats them as derived from sequences of long vowel followed by {{IPA|/n/}} and underlying {{IPA|/h/}}; the latter sound is converted to {{IPA|[<U+0294>]}} or deleted.<ref name="Piggott, Glyne, 1980, pp. 110-11">Piggott, Glyne, 1980, pp. 110-111; Piggott's transcription of words containing long nasal vowels differs from those of Rhodes, Bloomfield, and Valentine by allowing for an optional {{IPA|[<U+0294>]}} after the long nasal vowel in phonetic forms.</ref> A study of the Southwestern Ojibwe (Chippewa) dialect spoken in Minnesota describes the status of the analogous vowels as unclear, noting that while the distribution of the long nasal vowels is restricted, there is a [[minimal pair]] distinguished only by the nasality of the vowel: ''giiwe'' {{IPA|[<U+0261>i<U+02D0>we<U+02D0>]}} "he goes home" and ''giiwenh'' {{IPA|[<U+0261>i<U+02D0>w<U+1EBD><U+02D0>]}} "so the story goes".<ref>Nichols, John, 1980, p. 6</ref> Other discussions of Ottawa phonology and phonetics are silent on the issue.<ref name="Valentine_NASAL_40"/><ref>Rhodes, Richard, 1985, p. xxiv</ref>

