==Grammar==
{{see also|Ojibwe grammar}}
[[File:AndrewBlackbirdHistoryGrammarP120.JPG|right|300px|thumb|Printed text with columns of English words and corresponding Ottawa terms. Page from Andrew Blackbird's 19th-century ''History of the Ottawa and Chippewa Indians of Michigan'', which includes a grammatical description of the Ottawa and Southwestern Ojibwe (Chippewa) dialects of Ojibwe.<ref>Blackbird, Andrew J., 1887, p. 120</ref> Retrieved April 12, 2009 from [http://www.archive.org/details/historyofottawac00blac History of the Ottawa and Chippewa Indians of Michigan: A grammar of their language, and personal and family history of the author].]] Ottawa shares the general grammatical characteristics of the other dialects of [[Ojibwe language|Ojibwe]]. Word classes include [[noun]]s, [[verb]]s, [[grammatical particle]]s, [[pronoun]]s, [[preverb]]s, and [[prenoun]]s.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, Ch. 3</ref> 

Ottawa [[Noun class#Algonquian languages|grammatical gender]] classifies nouns as either animate or inanimate.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, p. 113</ref> Transitive verbs encode the gender of the grammatical [[Object (grammar)|object]], and [[Intransitive verb|intransitive]] verbs encode the gender of the grammatical [[Subject (grammar)|subject]], creating a set of four verb subclasses.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 114<U+2013>121, 130<U+2013>135</ref> The distinction between the two genders also affects verbs through [[Agreement (linguistics)|agreement]] patterns for number and gender.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 114<U+2013>121</ref> Similarly, [[demonstrative]] pronouns agree in gender with the noun they refer to.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, p. 116</ref>

===Morphology===
{{main|Ottawa morphology}}

Ottawa has complex systems of both [[inflection]]al and [[Derivation (linguistics)|derivational]] morphology. Inflectional morphology has a central role in Ottawa grammar. Noun inflection and particularly verb inflection indicate grammatical information through the use of prefixes and suffixes that are added to word stems.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 104<U+2013>105</ref>

Notable grammatical characteristics marked with inflectional prefixes and suffixes include:

#A distinction between [[Grammatical person#Additional persons|obviative]] and [[Grammatical person#Additional persons|proximate]] third person, marked on both verbs and nouns.<ref name="Valentine, J. Randolph 2001, pp. 623">Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 623<U+2013>643</ref>
#Extensive marking on verbs of inflectional information concerning [[Grammatical person|person]].<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, Chapters 5<U+2013>8; pp. 62<U+2013>72</ref>
#[[Grammatical number|Number]] (singular and plural).<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, p. 178</ref>
#[[Grammatical tense|Tense]].<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 759<U+2013>782</ref>
#[[Linguistic modality|Modality]].<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, p. 759</ref>
#[[Evidentiality]].<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 830<U+2013>837</ref>
#[[Negation (linguistics)|Negation]].<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 837<U+2013>856</ref>

Prefixes mark grammatical person on verbs, including first person, second person, and third person.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 62<U+2013>72</ref> Nouns use combinations of prefixes and suffixes to indicate [[Possession (linguistics)|possession]]. Suffixes on nouns mark [[Grammatical gender|gender]],<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 177<U+2013>178</ref> [[Locative case|location]],<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 743<U+2013>748</ref> [[diminutive]],<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 185<U+2013>190</ref> [[pejorative]],<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 190<U+2013>193</ref> and other categories.<ref>See Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, Ch. 5 for an extensive survey.</ref> Significant agreement patterns between nouns and verbs involve gender, [[Grammatical number#Singular versus plural|singular and plural]] number, as well as obviation.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, Chs. 4<U+2013>8</ref>

Ottawa derivational morphology forms basic [[word stem]]s with combinations of word [[Root (linguistics)|roots]] (also called ''initials''), and [[affix]]es referred to as ''medials'' and ''finals'' to create words to which inflectional prefixes and suffixes are added.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 318<U+2013>335</ref> Word stems are combined with other word stems to create [[Compound (linguistics)|compound]] words.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 335, 515<U+2013>522</ref>

Innovations in Ottawa morphology contribute to differentiating Ottawa from other dialects of Ojibwe. These differences include: the reanalysis of person prefixes and word stems;<ref name="Valentine, J. Randolph 2001, pp. 59"/> the loss of final /-n/ in certain inflectional suffixes;<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 18<U+2013>19</ref> a distinctive form for the verbal suffix indicating doubt;<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 1994, pp. 427<U+2013>428</ref> and a distinctive form for the verbal suffix indicating plurality on [[intransitive verb]]s with grammatically inanimate subjects.<ref name="Valentine, J. Randolph, 1994, p. 430">Valentine, J. Randolph, 1994, p. 430</ref>

The most significant of the morphological innovations that characterize Ottawa is the restructuring of the three person prefixes that occur on both nouns and verbs. The prefixes carry grammatical information about grammatical person (first, second, or third). Syncope modifies the pronunciation of the prefixes by deleting the short vowel in each prefix.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 63<U+2013>64</ref>

{| class="wikitable" border="2" align="center" cellpadding="3"
|+ Personal prefixes added to consonant-initial stem
|-
!width = "125"|'''English'''
!width = "125"|'''Non-Syncopating Dialects'''
!width = "125"|'''Ottawa'''
|-
| (a) ''first-person prefix''|| ni- || n-
|-
| (b) ''second person prefix''|| gi- || g-
|-
| (c) ''third-person''|| o- || <U+2014> (no form)
|-
|}

The third-person prefix /o-/, which occurs with both nouns and verbs, is completely eliminated in Ottawa.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, p. 64</ref> As a result there is no grammatical marker to indicate third-person on inflected forms of nouns or verbs. For example, where other dialects have ''jiimaan'' "a canoe" with no person prefix, and ''ojimaan'' "his/her canoe" with prefix ''o-'', Ottawa has ''jiimaan'' meaning either "canoe" or "his/her canoe" (with no prefix, because of syncope).<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 64<U+2013>67, 82<U+2013>83</ref> Apart from the simple deletion of vowels in the prefixes, Ottawa has created new variants for each prefix.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 1994, pp. 143<U+2013>147</ref> Restructuring of the person prefixes is discussed in detail in [[Ottawa morphology]].

===Syntax===
[[Syntax]] refers to patterns for combining [[word]]s and [[phrase]]s to make [[clause]]s and [[Sentence (linguistics)|sentence]]s.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, p. 916</ref> Verbal and nominal inflectional morphology are central to Ottawa syntax, as they mark grammatical information on verbs and nouns to a greater extent than in English (which has few inflections, and relies mainly on word order).<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, p. 918</ref> Preferred [[word order]]s in a simple [[Transitivity (grammatical category)|transitive]] sentence are verb-initial, such as [[verb<U+2013>object<U+2013>subject]] (VOS) and [[verb<U+2013>subject<U+2013>object|VSO]]. While verb-final orders are avoided, all logically possible orders are attested.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 934<U+2013>935</ref> Ottawa word order displays considerably more freedom than is found in languages such as English, and word order frequently reflects [[Discourse analysis|discourse]]-based distinctions such as [[Topic (linguistics)|topic]] and [[Focus (linguistics)|focus]].<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 951<U+2013>955</ref>

Verbs are marked for grammatical information in three distinct sets of inflectional paradigms, called [[Ojibwe grammar#Verbs|Verb orders]]. Each order corresponds generally to one of three main sentence types: the Independent order is used in [[Sentence (linguistics)|main clauses]], the Conjunct order in [[Dependent clause|subordinate clauses]], and the Imperative order in [[Imperative mood|commands]].<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 991<U+2013>996</ref>

Ottawa distinguishes [[yes-no question]]s, which use a verb form in the Independent order, from content questions formed with the Ottawa equivalents of [[Interrogative words|"what", "where", "when", "who"]] and others, which require verbs inflected in the Conjunct order.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, pp. 975<U+2013>991</ref>

Ottawa distinguishes two types of grammatical [[Grammatical person|third person]] in sentences, marked on both verbs and animate nouns. The [[Grammatical person#Additional persons|proximate]] form indicates a more salient noun phrase, and [[Grammatical person#Additional persons|obviative]] indicates a less prominent noun phrase. Selection and use of proximate or obviative forms is a distinctive aspect of Ottawa syntax that indicates the relative discourse prominence of noun phrases containing third persons; it does not have a direct analogue in English grammar.<ref name="Valentine, J. Randolph 2001, pp. 623"/>

==Vocabulary==
Few vocabulary items are considered unique to Ottawa.<ref name="Valentine, J. Randolph, 1994, p. 430"/> The influx of speakers of other Ojibwe dialects into the Ottawa area has resulted in mixing of dialects that were historically distinct. Given that vocabulary spreads readily from one dialect to another the presence of a particular vocabulary item in a given dialect is not a guarantee of the original source of the item.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 1994, pp. 430<U+2013>431</ref> Two groups of [[function word]]s are characteristically Ottawa: the sets of demonstrative pronouns and interrogative adverbs are both distinctive relative to other dialects of Ojibwe. Although some of the vocabulary items in each set are found in other dialects, taken as a group each is uniquely Ottawa.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 1994, pp. 424, 428</ref>

===Demonstrative pronouns===
Ottawa uses a set of [[demonstrative]] pronouns that contains terms unique to Ottawa, while other words in the set are shared with other Ojibwe dialects. Taken as a group the Ottawa set is distinctive.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 2001, p. 18</ref> The following chart shows the demonstrative pronouns for: (a) Wikwemikong, an Ottawa community; (b) Curve Lake, an Eastern Ojibwe community; and (c) Cape Croker, an Ottawa community that uses a mixed pronoun set. The terms ''maaba'' 'this (animate)', ''gonda'' 'these (animate)', and ''nonda'' 'these (inanimate)' are unique to Ottawa.<ref>Valentine, J. Randolph, 1994, p. 424</ref>

